{{Taxobox | domain = [[Bacteria]] | phylum = [[Proteobacteria]] | classis = [[Betaproteobacteria]] | ordo = [[Burkholderiales]] | familia = [[Comamonadaceae]] | genus = '''''Ideonella''''' | genus_authority = Malmqvist et al. 1994, gen. nov.<ref name="a.c.parte">{{cite web|url=http://www.bacterio.cict.fr/ijk/ideonella.html|title=Ideonella|author=A.C. Parte|publisher=|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref> | type_species = ''Ideonella dechloratans''<ref name="a.c.parte"/> | subdivision_ranks = Species | subdivision ={{Plainlist| * ''[[Ideonella azotifigens|I. azotifigens]]'' * ''[[Ideonella dechloratans|I. dechloratans]]'' * ''[[Ideonella sakaiensis|I. sakaiensis]]''}} }}
'''''Ideonella''''' is a genus of [[Comamonadaceae]] bacteria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uniprot.org/taxonomy/36862|title=Ideonella|publisher=|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref>
== Applications ==
=== ''Ideonella sakaiensis'' === {{Main|Ideonella sakaiensis}} In 2016 [[Ideonella sakaiensis|''I. sakaiensis'']] was shown to degrade [[Polyethylene terephthalate|PET]], a [[polymer]] widely used in food containers, bottles and synthetic fibers. Adhered to a low-grade PET film, the bacteria used two novel [[enzyme]]s to decompose the plastic into two environmentally benign substances, which served as their main food source.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-species-of-bacteria-eats-plastic-1457636401|title=New Species of Bacteria Eats Plastic|last=Long|first=Kat|date=March 10, 2016|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|issn=0099-9660|access-date=2016-03-11}}</ref>
A colony of ''I. sakaiensis'' could completely degrade a low-grade plastic water bottle in six weeks. Higher-grade PET products would require heating and cooling to weaken it before bacteria could start eating.<ref name=":0" />
The bacteria could also be used to reduce industrial waste during plastics manufacturing.<ref name=":0" />
