{{Unreferenced stub|auto=yes|date=December 2009}}
A '''LNG (liquefied natural gas) pier''' is a specialized kind of working [[pier]] designed for the loading and offloading of [[liquefied natural gas]] from ships to shore based tanks. 

A typical LNG pier could accommodate [[LNG carrier]]s from 138,000 cubic metres to 200,000 cubic metres in capacity. The pier would have at least one {{convert|44|in|mm|adj=mid|-diameter}} liquid unloading line using [[cryogenic]] transfer pumps to transfer the LNG to the [[LNG storage tank]]s on shore.

Some of these piers are very long, up to {{convert|4000|ft}}, in order to not have to dredge and blast underwater, in order to reach to the depth needed to accommodate LNG tanker traffic.

